and possibly dust a few com-sats via EMP but the effects<br>
would be negligible.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I never completely gave up on it. I just stress that there's always the space assembled alternative.<br>
 I like to think of looking into  (more accurately, twisting somebody else's arm to get them to do the numbers for) a string of neutron bombs or some such reduced/eliminated lingering radiation technology for the first few dozen bombs.<br>
Another thing the space launch does is makes testing easier. No rapid-fire string of bombs, any single one which misfires dooming the entire mission. Build it, fire a single charge to test it. Fire a few charges for the next test. Go around the Moon and back for the next shakedown cruise, etc.<br>
<br>
 Personally, I completely ignore the EMP &quot;threat&quot;, having seen nothing but conjecture and calculation based on <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">entirely</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> different circumstances to show that it's a threat.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; To say that you favor an Orion launch but with the<br>
stipulation that it must take place outside the<br>
magnetosphere is as much as saying that you oppose<br>
the concept altogether.<br>
&gt; Using colossal chemical boosters to lift Orion to a 30,000<br>
mile high orbit eliminates all but the most emaciated EPPP<br>
ships from consideration. A pipsqueak Orion would be little<br>
better than a NTR and not be worth the effort.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>1)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> maybe going above the entire magnetosphere isn't necesary.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>2)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> a far cry from saying that I hate the entire concept of &quot;blasting nukes in space and poisoning the delicate ecosphere of the solar wind&quot; or &quot;perpetrating an evil militaristic plot to put thousands of bombs in space to power death-rays and mind-probing satellites to control people's lives&quot; or some such.<br>
 Blow off nukes in space. Thousands of them. I'll say the same thing to any audience, any time, any circumstances (I have frequent opportunity, living in the People's Republic of Boulder, with all the peace rallies going on nowadays. It's fun).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>3)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> What's wrong with collossal boosters? Truax thinks highly of them -the bigger the better.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>4)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> 30,000 miles may not be necessary (as in 1, above), and above all, it doesn't have to be <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">orbit</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->... Apogee of a highly eccentric trajectory, where the perigee might even be dangerously low in the upper atmosphere, might be enough.<br>
 Get it above the sensible atmosphere and (if it's determined for whatever reason that we do want to be extremely high when we set bombs off) fire up an ED tether to lift it to an elliptical trajectory.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>5)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Even the tiny &quot;emaciated&quot; 580 ton 10 meter ship is a pretty damn robust ship! Far and away more studly than anything else in consideration for space travel (&quot;studly&quot; hereby being added to the aerospace technical lexicon).<br>
I'll accept what the NASA EPPP studies said about the Mark 1 Gabriel ship. Doesn't sound too weak to me.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; Imagine the cost of applying minimum weight<br>
criterion to Orion. The safety factors would be razor<br>
thin...</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 For my money, drop the crew down to 6, or even the Mars Direct 4, and toss in a few dozen more tons of redundancies and spares &amp; tools (above the already &quot;Orion standard&quot; high concentration of such things).<br>
 Or else go with the Orion standard. You're underestimating the Sea Dragon and such breeds of BDBs.<br>
(Note the above numbers fit the 10 meter ship)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I can however imagine a 2500 ton Orion being lobbed<br>
to an altitude of 250 miles by conventional rockets before<br>
we start kicking pulse units out the back.<br>
&gt; The difference between giving a 2500 ton Orion a<br>
6000mph high toss with chemical boosters before lighting<br>
it up is a vastly more simple task that trying to orbit a<br>
much smaller beast with chemical engines</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Even if we're using Shuttle or Energia derived parts to lift the ~80 to 120 ton segments of a space assembled ship, I don't see the tremendous difficulty. Again, we're not building a variant of the IBB (corporate welfare station) We're talking about 100 ton chunks of steel, with huge forged steel nuts &amp; bolts and brackets and guy wires and by-god cotter pins holding it together (I've worked on an Army M.A.S.H. unit and many carnivals, and I see technology whcih would work perfectly well, and wouldn't be hard to assemble in EVA time -if we're talking a thing which wanted the ruggedness of this kind of connectors. Every see cargo containers loaded and fastened onto a rail flatbed or container ship?)<br>
<br>
I'll look into the numbers for the Sea Dragon, to see what it could do for a 2500-6000 ton cargo (the range given by G.Dyson for the 20 meter ship)<br>
<br>
The figures we have for the &quot;high-toss&quot; launch only lift the 10 meter ship to ~50 miles. Do you have a different source? (I don't have the book handy)<br>
If we have a Sea Dragon, the entire ~500 ton ship is in orbit in one shot... Gotta love those Colossal boosters -if they're the right sort of beast.<br>
