<br>
You have made some good points that have convinced me that Orion should be in orbit before we start nuking. So big HLLV’s it is.(until Mauk2's GCNR comes on line)<br>
 <br>
Quote -----------------------------------------<br>
<br>
&quot;No rapid-fire string of bombs, any single one which misfires dooming the entire mission. Build it, fire a single charge to test it. Fire a few charges for the next test. Go around the Moon and back for the next shakedown cruise, etc.&quot;<br>
<br>
I agree the required pulse rate is way too high to even consider a ground launch. I believe that a ground launch of a the 4000-ton Orion was said to require a pulse rate of 2 per second to achieve an average thrust of 2 g's. At an acceleration rate of 2 g's it would take about 280 seconds to reach orbit with an expenditure of 560 pulse units. <br>
<br>
In order to maintain that 2g acceleration a pulse unit would have to be loaded, chambered, armed and then fired out of the back at a velocity of 750 feet per second &lt;mach .78&gt; every 1/2 second.Thats quite a nuclear bomb machine gun. <br>
<br>
The shock absorbers would also have to be able to handle a complete compression and compliance stroke every 1/2 second. Assuming a 900,000kg pusher plate and a 8-meter compression / compliance stroke the pusher plate would be exerting a force on the structure of  27,000,000kg-m/sec every time it cycles. That’s quite a jolt taking place every ½ second.  I am not convinced that we can make a shock absorbing system work that fast.  I agree that things should be taken slow. <br>
<br>
Perhaps the best solution is as you say to send up 200 or 300 ton sections of a boiler plate Orion to LEO and put the ship together there. Once in space a conservative shakedown period  like the one you propose can be put into motion. I like that idea better than the high toss or ground launch because I have a feeling that we simply can’t make recoil, pulse unit feed, arming, and detonation  systems that can maintain a 120 pulse a minute rate. In my mind a pulse rate of  10 - 20 per minute would be exciting enough.<br>
<br>
I think that making HLLV’s  that can hurl two or three hundred tons a pop into LEO is well within our present capabilities since we were already there in 1968 with the SaturnV-D. cut and paste the link below into youyr browser to see my entry in the 200-300 ton to LEO HLLV war.<br>
<br>
http://www.geocities.com/CapeCanaveral/Galaxy/9585/hllv.jpg<br>
<br>
You made some good observations John thanks for your insights.<br>
<br>
NukePulse<br>
